Aug 31 2009 	Really bad hospitality	I would like to say something nice about this hotel. Because certainly it has some nice features. But bad customer service overshadows even the most praise-worthy amenities. So instead, I'm going to give what may seem like an unbalanced review of my four nights at the Grand Mercure Xidan, by noting what's wrong with this hotel, starting with my run-in with the health club staff. As some reviewers have noted before me, this hotel quizzically requires guests to bring ineffectual &quot;bathing caps&quot; in the pool. Most foreigners don't bring these Chinese accessories on vacation, but staff are more than happy to give you one at the desk...and add the cost to your room tab. I headed down to the pool with my 8-year old nephew on my first day at the hotel, was informed of the &quot;bathing cap rule&quot;, and the kind girl at the desk lent me one of a handful of caps that she said were left over from other guests. I had explained to her that it didn't make sense to buy these caps for a few uses only. Problem solved. The next day at the pool we borrowed caps again. But on the third day, the desk was staffed by a guy who insisted that we buy one. Not only did he insist, but he did so in such a way that would make one question how he ever got a job in the hospitality industry. His behaviour was belittling and disdainful. He claimed I was lying when I told him that for the past few days I had been borrowing one, then he tried ignoring me hoping that I would go away, then he took on a really nasty tone. Not one to take treatment like that lightly (especially when I'm a paying guest), I called the duty manager, who patiently listened to my grievance, but in the end backed up the staff member (claiming that there were no used bathing caps available), and bafflingly offered me a fruit basket for my trouble(?!?!), proposing to examine the &quot;swim cap&quot; policy more thoroughly the next day. In the end, I conceded and bought the bathing cap - it was either that or not use the pool - but I was left with a very sour impression of the hotel. Every time my nephew and I used the pool after that, the desk guy glowered at us and couldn't even be cordial.Even before that encounter, the tendancy toward bad service had already been established at this hotel. On the second day, I asked the concierge how to get to the Temple of Heaven. After some confusion about what I was asking she brushed me off toward the bell boy who spoke virtually no English and directed me north instead of south. When I challenged him on it, he went and got someone else who gave me the correct directions to the south. Makes me wonder - if I can't get simple directions in English to one of the top 5 tourist attractions in Beijing, what good is the concierge?!?As for the amenities themselves, one of our first observations was the stench of the lobby washrooms. I can only surmise that it is a permanent problem because it didn't abate the whole four days we were there. Our room was uninspired - it overlooked a weed-infested inner courtyard that looks like it used to be a pool, and a building under construction next door. The tv remote control buttons were sticky and hard to operate. But worst of all was the closet-like bathroom - it was badly in need of some upkeep. The grout between the tiles was worn away, the toilet bowl had permanent stains, and every time I opened the bathroom door there was a bang from overhead (?!?) I chose this hotel based on positive reviews that I read here and because I am a loyalty member of the parent company. Yes there are some good things about this hotel, but I question how any of them matter in the face of such sub-standard treatment of guests. Needless to say, I will never be back and I recommend that you all give it a pass.	
