Nov 1 2007 	Just OK	Stayed here last week for 3 nights. I agree with another reviewer who rated it &quot;OK.&quot; That's all it was - just OK.Some of the check-in staff do not speak very good English (eg I asked for a safety deposit box and she replied - what kind of breakfast box do you want??????).We had a room on the 8th floor. It was OK - very old and tired; really could use a makeover. Bathroom was OK but old, some of the tiles were marked and cracked. Our room actually looked out onto the street below, so no building work.Breakfast was mediocre at best. Some of the drinking glasses were very dirty. Food looked totally unappetizing so decided not to even try it.On the good side - we ate from the room service menu twice and it was well-priced and the food was good. We tried local and western dishes and everything was good. The biggest problem was actually getting a menu, as there wasn't one in the room - had to go down to reception and beg for one (nobody answered the phone when I tried calling from the room).As others have stated - most taxi drivers know this hotel as the Marco Polo. Even though one needs a taxi to get anywhere from anywhere in Beijing, I found that a lot of taxi drivers refused to take us to the hotel (ie from Silk Street), saying it was too far away. I noticed many other hotels that looked a lot more central and a lot nicer than this one - this has absolutely nothing to recommend it.Having said that - I can't really complain about anything specific. It was just OK. Beds were comfortable, room was large. But I wouldn't stay there again and would rather pick something newer and better located.	
Oct 14 2007 	It's OK	We used the Grand Mercure as a base for a four night stay in Beijing. This certainly wasn’t the worst hotel we’ve ever stayed in, but certainly not the best. Hotels in Beijing were quite expensive when we booked, so after much research and deliberation we opted for the Grand Mercure, Beijing. As some people have previously mentioned, this used to be called to Marco Polo, so if you are using a taxi from the airport (as we did) it might be worth telling the driver that’s where you’re going. First impressions weren’t bad, the bell hops took our luggage from the taxi and we proceeded to check in, however, when we went to our room, there was no bellhop, so we grabbed our bags our self and headed up. The lobby was clean and spacious with a bar at the back, small gift shop, concierge, tour operator and business centre. The room was large, but it was showing signs of wear and tear, however, it was clean. There were many reminders of the hotels previous identity - on the robes, towels, and drink coasters. I found this quite frankly to be a bit shoddy and lazy – these are very easy things to fix. Our room unfortunately overlooked a building site. We had paid for breakfast in the room rate, which by Chinese standards was very expensive. Whilst the breakfast was plentiful and featured a wide range of items, I think we’d have been just as happy going Starbucks next door. On two of the four mornings we were questioned about whether we had paid for the breakfast in our rate, make sure your have two copies of your reservation, you’ll need one at check in, and keep hold of the second one just in case. The hotel has a swimming pool, sauna and steam room – be warned, you need to wear a swimming hat. We didn’t find this area of the hotel very pleasant and actually didn’t use the facilities.  My biggest disappointment with the hotel was with the tour operator. We booked a tour to see the Ming Tombs and Great Wall of China. DO NOT USE THE HOTEL’S TOUR COMPANY. We were picked up at the designated time of 7:30am, and didn’t return back to the hotel until 7:45pm. We spent about one hour at the Ming Tombs and about one and a half hours at the Great Wall. The rest of the time was spent travelling, at a Jade factory, eating a pitiful lunch and at a silk factory. The tour was extremely expensive by Chinese standards. I would highly recommend you do some research before hand and make your own arrangements to visit these places. We were very disappointed with the tour, it was such a waste of precious time, and every where we went they were trying to sell us stuff. The tour company gets a kickback from the Jade factory and Silk factory, so it’s in their best interest to take you there. The hotel is conveniently located, you can easily walk to Tiananmen Square and there are plenty of shops around about. The subway is also located near by and is dirt cheap.	
Aug 24 2007 	4 star hotel with 2 star ambience	We arrived to a room which smelled like staled rice crackers later to find it was the stench of mold. Our first room had black mold all over the shower and air conditioner. After a long night of trying to sleep, we asked to change our room. Our second room was a smoke filled room. One bed gave us some type of flea bites. The breakfast bufet was the least desirable. The staff were all new since the hotel was recently converted from the Marco Polo hotel. Registration took approximately 1 hour. The gift shop consisted of a closet without any postcards. Our tour guide said that this hotel was known as the second best 4 star hotel in Beijing . I think you if you are planning to visit Beijing you should try a 5 star hotel.Unhappy, US	
Aug 22 2007 	Mis-represented as New Hotel !	Spent 5 nights at Grand Mercure Xidan earlier this month. While it is in a good location, close to metro stations, this is a largish hotel (around 400 rooms) that doesn't live up to the grand mercure chain reputation and leaves a lot to be desired. During my trip, we stayed at 4 locations - Nanjing, Beijing, Shanghai, and Xian - and this was by far the worst not only in terms of value for money but in every way!I stayed there with my 18y.o. son and we had a magazine promotional deal which said it was a &quot;new&quot; hotel.Well, it might have been new in the 1980s when it was built and known - as it still is to most taxidrivers - as The Marco Polo. But now it is a very tired spot in desperate need of a make-over. The rooms are not sound-proofed to the level we expect today - but in their favour they do have some inter-connecting family rooms, which are often hard to find. Even the bath-towels, mats and robes still bore the insignia of &quot;Marco Polo&quot; so it has evidently been a walk-in-walk-out takeover. The towels are threadbare; the bathmats unravelling. Yes, the bathroom is still serviceable and must have been very smart back in the early 80s as this is the style of fitting there, but overall this is NOT a quality hotel. The carpets are stained, the curtains are well past their use-by date and are no longer &quot;block-out&quot; by any standard, and the TV was one of the old clunkers with very few channels to select from! Lighting was dim and desperate, and we received minimal re-charge of our toiletries even though we were there for 5 full days. The bed linen was adequate, but not new, and the cupboards were de-laminating, though the safe appeared adequate. Our room on the 8th floor overlooked the festering rooftop above the restaurant several floors below, and featured overgrown &quot;garden&quot; and slush. Peering through the Beijing air pollution, we could barely see the opposite side of the large Avenue in front of us; however, this street view will be the better aspect as soon as the building that is currently being erected next door goes up a few more floors. Workmen are on it from crack of dawn, so a room with that view will be noisy as each successive floor is constructed! (They have constructed about 6 floors to date, so plenty more to go up! ) Given the very close proximity to Tianamen Square and major tourist areas, I can see the owners of this hotel have purchased for future position and not for current premises. I'd suggest it will be a future &quot;tear-down&quot; as are many buildings/hutongs in Beijing. There is a reasonably sized &quot;Roman-style&quot; swimming pool in the basement 3 levels below ground, and a spa that could take about 16 people, with a life-guard-cum-attendant who points at the signs (in English) and ensures one never steps out of line, though I woulnd't like to really need his life-saving skills - too close for comfort; one couldn't relax under his gaze. And they make you sign to buy their (too small) swimming caps before you are allowed into the pool! Use of the &quot;business centre&quot; is a joke. One ancient computer works slowly, with a keypad that jumps everywhere, and they overcharge you to use it! Breakfast was included in our promotional deal, and the buffet closes at 9:30a.m. SHARP. We weren't the only ones we saw caught out by this. Not that it is a good buffet; it offers an odd selection, trying to offer &quot;American&quot; style breakfast but not really making it, and very few fresh fruits or yoghurts suited to a light Australian diet. Quite a bit of Japanese-style items served, and a little cheese &amp; crackers, and tired looking muffins &amp; danish pastries. Take your own tea-bags if you want a decent cuppa! And don't expect much by way of service. The staff here are poorly trained and really need to practice their smiles (and uniform washing and wearing!) in time for the Olympics! The adjective &quot;surly&quot; comes to mind! Yet, given the rush to supply desperately needed tourist accommodation in time for next year's anticipated influx, I imagine the Grand Mercure Xidan will continue to get away with charging too much and giving too little. We were never given a map (we bought a very good fold-out laminated one at the foreign bookstore near the enormous shopping centre around the Hyatt Hotel)but only saw one on the last day when we needed to collect tickets from the concierge desk.  I'd chosen this hotel based on its proximity to sights as well as because of the promotion. Be aware that, given that taxis are cheap enough in Beijing and the scale of walking what might appear to be a few blocks is really quite a bit further than one might initially be lulled into thinking is a walkable distance, location of a hotel probably need not be your highest priority when selecting accommodation in Beijing. Because this is inner-city, it has the drawbacks that not many little restaurants are open after 8p.m., and certainly very few after 9:p.m. - we wanted something around then, and ended up with a walkable choice of KFC, McDonalds, Gloria Jeans, or a sushi-train type of place (we were their final customers at just before 10p.m. ) I think it would be as easy to be further out, use the Metro more - they are building new lines at a furious pace, and the trains are good, if very cramped at times (still not as bad as Tokyo) - and in a nicer hotel rather than stay at the Marco Polo/Grand Mercure. I certainly wouldn't choose it if visiting for the Olympics. There are closer, and what appear nicer, accommodations than this to spend my hard-earned dollars in.	
