Oct 24 2005	Great hotel	I stayed at the Marco Polo in late September 2005 and loved it. The staff all speak English and are very helpful; the breakfast was great; the fitness centre, though small, had all I needed; and it was well located, being only about 50 metres from the Xi Dan underground station, which is a 2 yuan ride to Tien An Men Square and the Forbidden City. Being upgraded to a junior suite was a real bonus! I will stay here again if I go back to Beijing and recommend it unreservedly to everyone.	
Oct 13 2005	Marco Soso	I stayed at this hotel for 4 nights just last week. Yes, it is a good location, and yes, it was clean. That's about it. The breakfast was not very good, runny eggs, undercooked bacon, unattentive wait staff and a chef that didn't want to cook.The rooms are very plain and out dated. Toilet paper is more like sand paper. Thin towels and they didn't want to give us anymore unless we turned in the ones we had. The carpet seems clean, but looks very used, in the rooms and in the hallways.The lobby staff was nice, but none of the doormen we encountered spoke english, and were unable to help with making sure our taxi driver knew where to take us. Thankfully, we had a business card that had the major sites written in Chinese that we could show to our driver.We also stayed four nights at the Marriott Beijing West, what a difference! See review on Marriott for more info.	
Oct 13 2005	Rate it 7 out of 10	The good: 1) Spacious rooms, nice linen, and the concierge will be quite keen to upgrade you if you are not happy with your room. All you need to do is politely complain, and they will come to your aid. We got a room facing an enormous construction site, and since they work 24/7 in Beijing, we decided to complain. We got a fancy suite facing the main street, which was quiet; the bathrooms are quite large with both a shower and a bath-tub (bath tub not reccomended though - black spots spitting out of the faucet and yellow water put us off a bit)2) People are bangig on about location in some of the reviews. I seriously don't understand the complaint. Mind you, Beijing is an enormous city, and ridicolously crowded, which in itself makes it a hard place for pedestrians; furthermore, taxi's are affluent and so cheap that it is hard to believe. We never paid more than about 2 USD almost anywhere we went, so in my world, it doesn't really matter where you are in this city, as long as you are somewhere inside the city, and not out by the airport or near a cest pit somewhere. Taxi is your key, and the easiest way to get around. Bring a map to show to cab drivers with names in Chinese - it will make everything a lot easier. 3) Staff was helpful, albeit language is an issue - but that was expected, so it didn't really matter.The bad:1) I mentioned all the construction in Bejing - which again leads to a lot of dust and dirt. Beijing isn't the cleanest city in the world, and this fact goes badly with carpets. Even though this hotel is fairly new, it looked old mainly due to the filthy carpeting throughout the hotel. The Chinese are also famous for their &quot;spitting in the streets&quot; habbit; I know a lot of guests wear their shoes inside; all this add to the icky feeling you get when you take your shoes off after a long day and stick your bare feet on a rather filthy rug. I have never really used hotel slippers that much before, but in this location they came in handy.2) The staff at the breakfast buffé needs to change their attitude and do a better job. They tend to be a bit snippy and the are not attentive at all when food items run out, when you want more tea or honney and the like; 3 out of 5 days they were out of scrambled eggs and other things; all three times I had to ask them to sort some more out. No biggie, but three times over you start getting a bit annoyed, especially when the buffé is expensive, and not that great.3) They brag about their indoor pool; it is OK but nothing fancy. What is worse, they force you to buy a swimming cap for 60 Juan before you are allowed to enter. A bit cheeky I thought, and it made everyone look ridiculous. One size does NOT fit all Europeans. But the pool was clean, which is good (it really should be in a 4 star so...).All in all: a good deal, and it is a great starting point for tours and trips to various sites outside and inside the city. If they got rid of their rugs and got wooden floors or similar instead, then it would be 5 star, and a much better, and more hygenic experience, for all guests. This will not bother brits - and Americans for that matter - since they seem to have the same nasty habbits with rugs as the Chinese - and many other countries for that matter, but for all Scandinavians who are accustomed to materials which makes it easy to dodge dirt and not collect it over time, the rugs at this hotel can be slightly off-putting. 1 point off for the breakfast staff, and two points off for filty, scrubby rugs: I give it 7 out of 10.	
Oct 12 2005	Marco Polo? Marco Polo!	Just like Beijing's Panjiayuan Antique Market, this place delivers the &quot;goods,&quot; at a deep discount relative to what you would pay in the U.S. or Europe. At $110 (U.S.) or 891 Chinese Yuan Renminbi per night (all charges and breakfast included) this hotel is a great deal. The rooms are modern with comfortable beds to ease your jet lag. The pool, fitness center, sauna, and steam room are blissful (see photos).Internet access is available from your room, there is a business center in the lobby, and most staff speak English. But it's the complimentary breakfast buffet, with all the Western and Chinese standards and a few extras (such as my favorite Swiss cereal) that really seals the deal. Located in Beijing's booming Xi Dan area, it's a short walk to the Xi Dan metro and its surrounding complex of high-end retail shops and restaurants. There's a 5-story underground mall connected to the metro, with a 3-D movie theatre and swimming pool/skating rink. The new Capital Times Square retail complex features luxury brand stores (with prices like in the U.S.) but also has an excellent food court (with prices much lower than in the U.S.). For example, a Dairy Queen Blizzard costs 90 cents. From the hotel, it's a short cab ride to many of the major sites, including The Forbidden City, Tiananmen Square, the Temple of Heaven, or the ritzy Wangfujing Street/Oriental Plaza/Grand Hyatt shopping area (all under $5 rides). If you take the subway, it's less than a dollar. The hotel concierge can arrange tours to The Great Wall or anywhere else. You can change money at the airport (keep receipt and you can convert it back upon departure) or at the hotel desk. A few tips: Although 100 Yuan is only about $12, you will be able to buy meals for much less than this, and even brand-name (e.g., Adidas, Diesel, and Lacoste) &quot;knock-offs&quot; or fakes for less than this at popular tourist markets like Ya Show and Hong Qiao Shichang. So, make sure you have some small Yuan bills because, on rare occasions, if you hand out 100 Yuan for a 20 Yuan cab ride, Buddha statue, etc., you might get some counterfeit bills in your change. While shopping, remember to start of by offering a third or even a quarter of the asking price. Haggling is generally expected (and encouraged) here! In fact, even in hotels, high-end stores, and airport shops, you'll see that you can often easily lower the price by asking for their &quot;best price&quot; or if you don't seem interested, they'll offer you the &quot;discount price.&quot;	
Oct 10 2005	New hotel in Beijing	My wife &amp; I had a four nights stay in the new hoel in Beijing a few blocks west of Teinanmin Square.Very good location for touring all attractions in Beijing.Our corner room was large, quite, clean and comfortableWill stay there again next time.	
Oct 6 2005	Lovely Boutique Hotel in the Middle of Smog City	We stayed at the Marco Polo for 8 nights and found it to be very good value due to an American Express special 3 nights for the price of 2 (each night was around US$105+15%). The hotel has an excellent location, situated between two subway stations on two different lines- this alone is almost worth the price of the room.We were upgraded to a room on the Executive Floor (rm1046) with a view of the construction site next door. The bathroom was beautiful- separate glass-enclosed shower, bathtub, marble detailing, great towels. The bed is very comfortable and furnished with feather quilt and pillows. TV has HBO, 3 news stations, ESPN and various Chinese channels.Staff are generally helpful and speak basic English (for excellent service and English, check for a chap called &quot;Winter&quot; at the Front Desk).A western breakfast buffet is served on the Executive Floor and drinks and cocktails are served at certain times throughout the day. Ok, now for the brickbats.-Although we LOVED the luxurious feel of the feather bedding, we had some problems with allergies and requested non-feather bedding. Our request was met with some limp pillows and ratty blankets.-The special rate of our room entitled us to breakfast for 1 person for the 8 nights we were staying. We negotiated with Winter at the Front Desk to divide the breakfasts between us (so, instead of 8 breakfasts for 1 person over 8 days, we would have 4 breakfasts for 2 people over 4 days)- we were very pleased with the arrangement however the next day after having breakfast, we were presented with a bill from the 'butler' on the 10th floor for one breakfast. She was very obstinate, had no idea about good customer service and told us (get this) that if we didn't pay, she would get Winter (the front desk clerk) to pay(!) so we had to get the manager in who cleared things up. This conflict played out throughout our stay, which made it a bit stressful during breakfast! By the way, breakfast really wasn't worth all the hassle- the usual hotel buffet spread, no Chinese options and TEA-BAGS! Can you believe it?!-We can't say for sure what happened, but my partner 'lost' US$20 from some money he had (unsuccessfully) hidden and I 'misplaced' some dried persimmons I'd brought from Singapore. OK, we should have used the safe for the money, but you'd think that some dried fruit would be safe from pilfering fingers?!-ROOM SERVICE FOOD IS AWFUL! One night, after doing 10KM hike on the Great Wall, we came back too late to dine at our favourite restaurant and ordered some Chinese items from the room service menu- quite possibly the most awful room service meal we've ever had the misfortune to digest. If you MUST eat in your room, try to get some dim sum from the third floor restaurant delivered to your room.-Concierge is a joke- direct all inquiries to Winter. -Access to quality newspapers is terrible- they have only one copy of the International Herald Tribune and The South China Post on the 10th Floor and they guard it jealously- no taking it back to the room to enjoy at your leisure!	
